<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    Use a mini seed spreader for very small seeds when you want faster, more even distribution. Adjust the flow carefully and move at a steady pace to avoid clumping.
  </p>

  <p>
    For small batches or precise spacing, hand sowing may still be the better choice.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    It improves distribution — not precision.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best mini seed spreader for tiny seeds is one that provides consistent, controlled flow without overcomplicating the process.
  </p>

  <p>
    It’s a useful tool for improving efficiency, but it won’t replace careful planting entirely.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
